  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Memorial Requesting Release from Office
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your Majesty's generous heart has appointed me, a man of old service, to a place of honor in the court. Yet now, as my humble frame trembles with advancing years, I seek only the repose that comes with age.

    Reflecting upon history, I observe that the bond between ruler and subject ebbs and flows like the tides. In the chronicles of past dynasties, both exemplars and cautionary tales abound. When suspicion festers unexamined, shame inevitably follows like a shadow.

    Last year, I undertook a mission bearing your royal edict to the capital. In my carelessness, I failed to choose my companions wisely, and this negligence brought forth accusations that saw me stripped from service. This failure is mine alone—Heaven itself bears witness. My bones ache with the weight of this shame, and how could I dare lift my face to seek further favor?

    I humbly beseech Your Majesty: grant mercy to this aging, infirm servant, and take pity upon my tarnished name. If you would bestow your gracious approval, allowing me to spend my remaining years in peace, then shall I labor by day in the fields and read by night, steadfast in the way of the gentleman. And as the sun rises constant and the moon endures eternal, so too shall I offer daily prayers for Your Majesty's longevity and wisdom.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This memorial is a formal petition to resign from court office, written in the classical Korean bureaucratic style with allusions to Confucian virtues of loyalty, shame, and self-cultivation.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of day labor and night study references the Confucian ideal of constant self-improvement and moral cultivation.
  - key: ''
    value: The concluding astronomical references—sun and moon—are traditional metaphors for imperial virtue and constancy in East Asian political thought.
